text: Hello Cousins -  Looks like a grand movie ... much of it was filmed in Montréal with some locations standing in for Brooklyn, New York in 1952. Looking forward to seeing it as I'm in it playing a 'rude' Irish immigrant in the Thanksgiving Day Feast scene ... I'm a wee bit 'testy' and quite naturally fond of me liquor, and if I made the cut and therefor remain to be seen in close attendance to the resonant Irish voice of Irish Singer, Iarla O'Lionaird, as well as being being soundly chastised by Father Flood, played by Jim Broadbent. Ach, it was a grand day … touching you might say for it brought me back to my roots, somewhat, for it was in 1952 that we emigrated to Canada from Scotland. I hope you'll take the time to see the movie when finally released and to let me know how you felt about it.

text: from someone who has seen the movie - trust me it is NOT ABOUT A LOVE TRIANGLE. now i havent read the books so maybe the book was about the love triangle but the movie is definitely not. Instead it focuses more on the settling aspect of the story. You see this immigrant struggle so much with the concept of home. This is the protagonist's journey towards finding her identity, her home, her heart. You see her struggle with America.  As an immigrant myself, i identify with this movie so much. The hopes of the country, the bitter reality, the longing to be home, family, friends, new life, new job. The movie and Saroise perfectly captured the entire transformation. I know art is what is perceived by the eye and mind BUT i really really wished people would stop saying it is a love triangle drama. It is not. It was not shot that way. The role the irish fella plays in this movie is very minimal, there is a tiny small emotional affair- not even  an actual emotional affair, just the potential for one.

text: As an immigrant myself, I find this movie quite superficial... a beautiful happy-ending story. Where are the real difficulties of living abroad in a different culture, where no one understands the little things that belong to you, where foreigners are often seen as a threat...? It seemed to me a little condescending that after a limited period the main character had already forgotten her past to fully embrace her new life. It takes ages – if that is ever possible – to overcome that feeling of longing, the sense of not belonging somehow... one's soul divided between two countries. No, for me this movie did not touch reality in the slightest.
